post_text: From our school nurse: Letters went home this week for all students in 7th and 12th graders that are not up to date on vaccines. If you received a letter for your child please get the required vaccines by 9/9/2020. After this date, the law provides that students NOT IN COMPLIANCE with these requirements MUST BE EXCLUDED from school until the student provides verification of the immunization received, has a scheduled plan signed by the physician, or obtains an exemption signed according to the provisions of the law. This also applies to any student doing blended learning. If you have any questions please call the school nurse at 740-493-2881.

post_text:
The following is a message concerning our academic banquet, academic awards ceremonies, 8th grade graduation, and 2020 prom.

We are in the process of preparing awards for the academic banquet, awards day ceremony and 8th grade graduation. All awards and certificates have been ordered and are being printed out. Awards and certificates will be given out by appointment. Students will have their picture taken with their awards/certificates and will be posted on our school Facebook pages. Any student who cannot get their picture taken with their certificates will have them mailed home.

Some senior scholarships have been pushed back so we are going to hold off until we can have as many scholarship recipients in as possible in order to accurately represent each students actual awards.

We are still holding out hope that we can still have 2020 prom in some form. We will let students know as soon as possible what our plans are. It is postponed indefinitely but it has not been canceled in hopes that we will be able to have this special event for our seniors.

To the class of 2020, “The Class that Couldn’t be Stopped.”

We apologize that we couldn’t get a detailed plan out to you earlier but the directions for graduation from Governor Dewine were very fast-changing and we are just now able to get a detailed plan in place. We have gone through many different possible plans and scenarios in order to determine the best possible way to honor our graduates while also keeping the social distancing requirements in place in order to keep everyone safe. We believe that we have found the best way to accomplish both goals and get as close… More

post_text:
I don’t know who the originator of this post was but I do agree that our young people will come out of this with a perspective on life that previous generations haven’t had.

———————————————————-

Ohio schools have been out for over four weeks and if we go back May 1, we would be out for over seven weeks. If they cancel the rest of the school year, students would miss 2.5 months of education. Many people are concerned about students falling behind because of this. Yes, they may fall behind when it comes to classroom education...

But what if...

What if instead of falling “behind", this group of kids are ADVANCED because of this? Hear me out.

What if they have more empathy, they enjoy family…

post_text:
Senior Profile! 💚
Congratulations, Veronica! We’re so proud of you!

Veronica Lemaster is a dedicated young woman. Her favorite extracurricular activity at Western, for many years, has been cheering. As a junior she chose to attend the CTC. During her time at the CTC she has become a certified phlebotomist and certified in CPR and first aid. She has intent to go to college. She has recently been accepted to Southern State. Her senior year has consisted of helping at home more than she initially anticipated (but very appreciated for it all), a back surgery, long evenings and nights outside helping her father with his semi's, missing homecoming, and now working through this pandemic. Although her senior year isn't going anywhere near how we're all sure she had hoped and she has to miss out on a lot of things most seniors experience, her dedication to her family, to her cheer squad, to her schooling, to herself and her accomplishments thus far will always be remembered however.

From Mr. McFarland:

Health and Physical Education students. Your assignment until we return to school will be, a 10 minute workout and 20-30 minutes of cardio outside. The workout can be found on YouTube. Search: Fraser Wilson 10 minute bodyweight workout(before bed). This workout can be done anytime during the day. Do this Monday thru Friday. Your cardio workout can be walking, jogging, running, riding bike, playing a sport (basketball, throwing baseball/softball or throwing football) and doing daily chores. Cardio workouts should increase your heart rate and make the body sweat. Contact Mr. McFarland at my school email address if you have any questions and to let me know how you are doing with your assignment. Stay Healthy. Hope to see you all soon.

WHS Art Students: I understand many of you may not have a lot of art supplies on hand, especially since there was such short notice of the school closure. If some of you HAVE art supplies, and you’d like to continue to create, here is a challenge for you!
CREATE a work of art , in your choice of medium, that represents spring!
Spring can mean a lot of different things to people. I love it because everything gets a new start! My perennial garden is coming out of its dormant stage and spring flowers are in bloom!
Medium can be photography, sculpture, drawings, paintings, sidewalk chalk drawings, origami, play dough creations, natural found objects(twigs, leaves, rocks, etc.)or any other material you have available!

( Please post images with name, title,and medium. School appropriate images only.)

Also, please message me if you’d like to have some paper and watercolors. I will do my best to get them to you.

post_text: Due to a sharp increase in the number of flu cases in the past week we will be closing on Friday in order to give our custodians a chance to thoroughly clean both buildings. We’ve had at least 21 confirmed flu cases in just the elementary building since Friday morning. We had 100 students out today with 71 being in the elementary building. This has nothing to do with the coronavirus but it has everything to do with the flu which has definitely had a major impact on us throughout the winter. We hope that giving the kids an extra day away from each other will reduce the spread. If you have kids who are showing any signs please don’t send them to school. We have kids coming to school every single day with a fever over 100 when they walk in the building. That is just causing this to go on and on. Believe me if your kid is sick we will work with you on the attendance side so please keep them home so they can get better and not make anyone else sick.
